# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: robert-dipierdomenico
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] The **1924 Brownlow Medal** was the inaugural year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Victorian Football League (VFL) home and away season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] Edward 'Carji' Greeves of the Geelong Football Club won the medal by polling seven votes during the 1924 VFL season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] The following list shows the leading vote-getters for the 1924 Brownlow Medal.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] Edward 'Carji' Greeves was the winner, with George Shorten and Bert Chadwick runners-up.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] Greeves' outstanding season is further outlined by the fact that he is one of the youngest players to win the award, aged just 20 years 312 days at the time.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] Greeves' seven best-on-ground awards in just fourteen games played is another outstanding statistic.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] With vote inflation included (where 1 vote in 1924 equals 3 votes), Greeves is one of the most consistent vote-getters of all time, with an average of 0.81 votes per game throughout his 10-season career.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] The following list shows the teams whose players polled the most votes.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] Geelong topped the list with 11 votes, 7 of them made up by 'Carji' Greeves.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] The team that polled the most votes, Geelong, missed the 1924 VFL finals by two games, finishing 5th.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] The following list shows the players who topped their team for the most votes polled.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1924-brownlow-medal] The Brownlow Medal was presented to the player at League Headquarters, without the fanfare, glitz and glamour of the award today.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1927-brownlow-medal] The **1927 Brownlow Medal** was the fourth year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Victorian Football League (VFL) home and away season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1927-brownlow-medal] Syd Coventry of the Collingwood Football Club won the medal by polling seven votes during the 1927 VFL season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1929-brownlow-medal] The **1929 Brownlow Medal** was the sixth year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Victorian Football League (VFL) home and away season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1929-brownlow-medal] Albert Collier of the Collingwood Football Club won the medal by polling six votes during the 1929 VFL season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1929-brownlow-medal] A new provision was introduced to suspend Brownlow Medal voting during rounds when the state team was active to avoid disadvantaging the players selected in the team.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1929-brownlow-medal] This provision was not repeated in future years.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] The **1930 Brownlow Medal** was the seventh year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Victorian Football League (VFL) home-and-away season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] The award was won jointly by Stan Judkins of the Richmond Football Club, Harry Collier of the Collingwood Football Club, and Allan Hopkins of the Footscray Football Club.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] It was the first time more than one player won the award in the same year.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] Under the voting system in place at the time, the central umpire awarded one vote to the player he deemed best on the ground in each match.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] When the votes were counted on 17 September, three players tied for the most votes with four each: Harry Collier of the Collingwood Football Club, Allan Hopkins of the Footscray Football Club, and Stan Judkins of the Richmond Football Club.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] It was the first time there had been a tie for the award; however, at the time, the league did not recognise ties for the medal, and they needed to break the tie.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] The delegates of the Umpire and Permit Committee met on 19 September; it did not make a final decision, instead electing to defer the matter to the next full meeting of all League delegates.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] The delegates recommended that no medal be awarded, owing in large part to the informal votes.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] The full League met on 26 September and rejected the recommendation, instead awarding the medal to Judkins on the 'percentage of votes vs games' provision – Judkins polled his four votes from 12 games, compared with Hopkins' 15 games and Collier's 18 games.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] The outcome is viewed with irony, as the reason for Judkins' lower game count was that he was dropped to the seconds for the last five rounds due to poor form.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] In its 26 September meeting, the League appointed a subcommittee to revise the medal's rules, resulting in a new voting system and tiebreaker rule being established from the 1931 season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] In 1980, the league removed all tie-breakers from its Brownlow Medal procedure, and in 1989 elected to award retrospective Brownlow Medals to all players who had previously polled the most votes but lost on a tie-breaker.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1930-brownlow-medal] As such, Judkins, Hopkins and Collier are all now considered joint Brownlow Medallists for the 1930 season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1931-brownlow-medal] The **1931 Brownlow Medal** was the eighth year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Victorian Football League (VFL) home and away season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1931-brownlow-medal] Haydn Bunton of the Fitzroy Football Club won the medal by polling twenty-six votes during the 1931 VFL season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1931-brownlow-medal] Following the previous season's three-way tie, and the confusion which followed, the conditions governing the medal were amended.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1931-brownlow-medal] From this season, the umpire would award votes to the best three players on the ground – three votes to the best player, two to the second best, and one to the third best.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1931-brownlow-medal] The player with the most overall votes would win; in the event of a tie, the player with the most three-vote games would win, then the player with the most two-vote games.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1931-brownlow-medal] A new provision under which a player who had been suspended during the season became ineligible for the award was also added.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1932-brownlow-medal] The **1932 Brownlow Medal** was the ninth year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Victorian Football League (VFL) home and away season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1932-brownlow-medal] Haydn Bunton of the Fitzroy Football Club won the medal for the second consecutive year by polling twenty-three votes during the 1932 VFL season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1933-brownlow-medal] The **1933 Brownlow Medal** was the tenth year the award was presented to the player adjudged the fairest and best player during the Victorian Football League (VFL) home and away season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/1933-brownlow-medal] Wilfred Smallhorn of the Fitzroy Football Club won the medal by polling eighteen votes during the 1933 VFL season.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico was born in Hawthorn to parents Stefano and Antonietta, who had emigrated to Australia from Abbateggio, Italy.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico's parents were married by proxy, meaning they were married over the phone.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico began playing football in his early teens for local clubs East Hawthorn and North Kew before signing for VFL club Hawthorn as an eighteen-year-old.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] As a youngster, DiPierdomenico played cricket and would bowl left arm over the wrist.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Beginning his career with the Hawthorn Football Club in 1975, DiPierdomenico started slowly, playing 99 reserve-grade games as he flitted between first team and reserve-grade football.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] He kick-started his career in 1978, culminating in a best-on-ground performance in the 1978 VFL Grand Final.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico was initially assigned guernsey number #53, but subsequently wore number #9.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Typically, he was considered one of Hawthorn's best players.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] He was known for his toughness (which led to many trips to the Tribunal), and the moustachioed Dipper was one of the much-loved, and most media-covered characters in the VFL during the 1980s.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico won the Brownlow Medal, in 1986 tying with Greg Williams, who was playing for Sydney at the time.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] During that season, DiPierdomenico was considered very fortunate to have avoided the VFL tribunal, and consequent ineligibility for the Brownlow.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Later in the week, he would win his third Premiership medallion as the Hawks defeated Carlton by 42 points.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Late in the first quarter of the 1989 VFL Grand Final, DiPierdomenico was running backwards to take a mark when he was met solidly from behind by Geelong star Gary Ablett.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] The force of the collision broke several of DiPierdomenico's ribs and punctured one of his lungs.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Despite the pain, and being unaware of the extent of the damage, DiPierdomenico continued to play until the final siren, and Hawthorn won by a goal in one of the most famous grand finals of all time.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] He collapsed shortly after the game and was rushed to the casualty ward of St.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Vincent's Hospital, where doctors found out that DiPierdomenico had punctured a lung.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico went on to play 240 games and kick 130 goals with the Hawks, retiring in 1991, and participating in five day and four night premierships during one of the most successful eras that a VFL/AFL club has ever achieved.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] After DiPierdomenico retired, he became a popular media personality as a boundary rider with the Seven Network.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] After Seven lost the rights to broadcast AFL in 2001, DiPierdomenico continued his tradition as a boundary rider on radio station 3AW.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico also worked at Sky News Australia as their AFL expert in the mid-2000s.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] In the 1990s, DiPierdomenico made an appearance, along with Dermott Brereton and Adrian Barich, in a charity rugby league match and scored a try, and in comedic fashion dived over the line in a fashion similar to Superman to celebrate.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] In 2010, he was stood down from his role in the Auskick junior development program after making a racist remark regarding Gavin Wanganeen.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico made a cameo in the TV series *Neighbours* in 1999, and he appeared on the Channel 9 weight-loss show *Excess Baggage* in 2012.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Since 2019, he has been hosting the TV series *Dipper's Backyard BBQ Wars*.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Dipierdemenico appeared in adverts for department store Dimmeys in the 1990s.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] Dipper was the 7th person evicted on the seventh series of *I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!* in 2021.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] He is the first celebrity to bowl a strike in a sushi-eating challenge.
[src:robert-dipierdomenico/robert-dipierdomenico] DiPierdomenico is an advocate for incontinence awareness, taking a brave step to publicly bring attention to the taboo subject.
